sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TOPPED THE RANKINGS AFTER WINNING THE INNINGS.
On Friday, West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons took four for 38 as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to top the county championship.

However, their stay at the top may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up lost time in a rain-affected match against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling Somerset out for 83 in the morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire went on to post 94 runs in their first innings before being bowled out for 296, with England dropping Andy Caddick, who took three for 83.
Trailing by 213, Somerset started the second innings confidently before Simmons took to the field to tie them at 174 all out.
Essex, however, look confident of reclaiming the top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Souk secured them a solid win against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day needs, made 158 not out, his first championship century of the season, while Essex reached 372 not out and were 82 runs ahead in the first innings.
By the end Yorkshire had turned that into a 37-run lead but off-spinner Sooke dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hovering at 119 for five and praying for rain.

At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man left out for England, continued to silence his critics as he followed his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher who made 70 as Surrey closed on 429 for seven, leading by 234.
Derbyshire continued their hunt for their first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in the second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding innings defeat.
Australian Tom Moody took six for 82 but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, put Derbyshire on 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the disappointment of the weather affecting the game on the opening day, Kent stepped up and defeated Nottinghamshire 214-0.
They were held back by a rude 84 from Paul Johnson but ex-England fast bowler Martin McCaig took four for 55.
Kent reached 108 for three at stumps.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER NAMED CAPTAIN OF THE ENGLAND NATIONAL TEAM.
On Friday, the world's most expensive footballer Alan Shearer was elected the new captain of the England national team.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), succeeds Tony Adams, who led the team during the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss the first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer accepted the captaincy on a trial basis but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not make the post his own.
"I'm sure there will be no problems, I'm sure Alan is the man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was ready for it and really wanted it.
"It is very difficult to make a 100 percent conclusion about something like this in four days...
but he knows how to behave, he is respected by his teammates and he is aware of the situation in the team, although he plays up front." "
On Friday, striker Teddy Sheringham, who was Shearer's main teammate, withdrew from the Euro 96 squad with an injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BLOCKED AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

FC Rotor Volgograd is to play its next home game behind closed doors after fans pelted Dynamo Moscow players with bottles and stones during a 1-0 home defeat on Saturday that ended Rotor's brief stay at the top of the league.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on September 3.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup, was fined $ 1000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position, having played 11 games in the championship.
Being three points behind Alania and two points behind Dynamo Moscow, the Volgograd team has a game in reserve over the leaders and two over the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN ROBERTO DURAN IS FIGHTING WITH THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Stone Hands" Duran will enter the ring on Saturday in another attempt to extend his long career despite his age.
Duran, 45, will face little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in an untitled super middleweight bout in Panama.
This fight, Duran's first appearance on home soil in 10 years, is being called "The Return of a Legend" here, and Duran still talks like he's in his prime.
I am not retiring," Durand said in an interview with Reuters.

But people close to the boxer admit that the man who has won championship titles in four different weight categories - lightweight, featherweight, welterweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the best boxers in the world," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panamanian Boxing Association.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, is hoping that a win in the 10-round bout will entitle him to a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
In June in Atlantic City, Camacho defeated the Panamanian by controversial decision in a title fight.

TENNIS - TANGO, O'BRIEN SPRING TWINS UPSET UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday but Wimbledon finalist Maliwai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of upsets at the US Open.
Washington, seeded 11th, failed to repeat his miracle at Wimbledon, losing to "hot" wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour battle on the stadium court in two hours and 51 minutes.
Next door on the court, 10th seed Rios lost to another Wimbledon player - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean with a score of 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth seeded former champion Agassi had to claw his way out of a perilous 3-6 0-4 hole, winning 18 of the last 19 games against Indian Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the upstarts.
Washington, who rallied from 1-5 down to lose two sets in the third set to Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semifinals, looked poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title in New Haven two weeks ago, was serving in the third set at 5-4 before Washington came back into the game.
"I just kept telling myself: 'Keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting and maybe something will happen,'" said O'Brien, 26, who tied for 65th.
"I kept my composure and I'm proud of myself for that - normally I would have rolled up my tent and gone home."
The hardy O'Brien, a former U.S. college champion, fired 17 aces to finally conquer a restless Washington.
The fifth set stayed on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, having saved one break point with a forehand winner down the line, realized a backhand return and put O'Brien ahead 4-2.
The Texan scored two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for the win as Washington found the net with another backhand for 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and try to get him to play a little bit.
I think it took a little bit too long at a couple of points," Washington said.
But I think he served pretty well when it was needed." "

Taranto, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a suspension from this year's tournament at the All England Club, argued with and taunted fans during his lively two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
The noisy tribune supported the confused Chilean and booed the lanky American who absorbed all the attention.
I think I played very well today, very concentrated. "
The match went to the tie-break of the third set, which the American won with a score of 7:5 to the great surprise of the audience.
"I love the crowd if they boo me every day.
It fires me up, makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I was playing my best tennis in college when the fraternities were throwing beer on me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Rios did not appreciate Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I think that is not the point.
I think I played very badly.
It was hard to play at night.
The balls were flying very fast.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I play an American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel very good on the court. "
At the end of the match, Tarango sarcastically kissed the crowd and then shook his body towards the Rios fan sector in a mocking salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are openly rooting against me.
After the victory, I decided that I could stun them a little bit." "
RANDALL CUNNINGHAM HAS RETIRED FROM AMERICAN FOOTBALL.
Randall Cunningham, the greatest quarterback in National Football League history and one of the most athletic players ever to line up under center, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl winner, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the great Philadelphia fans for their support throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I am sad to leave, I am looking forward to spending more time with my family and doing other things that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. - He was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for fans both in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a broadcasting contract.
